      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are experiencing a case of \"gibberish\" in the soil, a common issue among green-thumbed gardeners. The lower leaves turning yellow could be a sign of poor drainage or perhaps a nutrient deficiency, like nitrogen. You might want to consider adding some compost to the soil, which can help improve drainage and provide essential nutrients. Also, make sure your plants aren't too close together, as this can lead to competition for resources, causing the lower leaves to yellow. Keep an eye on your plants and adjust your care as needed. Remember, every plant is a little different, so what works for one might not work for another. Happy gardening!",
